


# PHASE 2 — INGESTION PIPELINE

[## [SECTION: Exception Hierarchy — Why We Need Custom Exceptions]]

174
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:32,000
Now let's move to Phase 2. The ingestion pipeline.
This is how we get data into our system.

175
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:38,000
But before we write the ingestor, we need to define our exception hierarchy.
A proper exception hierarchy is one of the first signs of professional Python code.

176
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:44,000
Why do we need custom exceptions?
Because catching a generic Exception tells you nothing about what went wrong.

177
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:50,000
Was the database down? Did EDGAR rate limit us? Could we not parse the HTML?
Each of these requires a different recovery strategy.

178
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:56,000
With custom exceptions, you can catch exactly what you need.
And let everything else bubble up to a higher level.

179
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:02,000
Every exception in our application will inherit from a single base class.
We'll call it FinRAGError.

180
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:08,000
This allows us to catch any application-specific error with one except block if needed.
But we can still differentiate between different error types.

181
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:14,000
We never raise a bare Exception anywhere in our codebase.
Always use our own exception types.

182
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:20,000
Let's create the hierarchy.
At the root is FinRAGError.

183
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:26,000
Below it, we have five main categories.
StorageError for database and cache issues.

184
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:32,000
IngestionError for document ingestion problems.
ProcessingError for chunking and transformation errors.

185
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:38,000
RetrievalError for embedding and vector search errors.
And ConfigurationError for fatal misconfigurations.

186
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:44,000
Each of these will have more specific subclasses.
DatabaseConnectionError, DatabaseQueryError, CacheConnectionError, CacheOperationError.

187
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:50,000
SECFetchError, DocumentParseError, DuplicateFilingError.
ChunkingError, EmbeddingError, VectorSearchError.

188
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:56,000
Let me show you the complete exception hierarchy.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/utils/exceptions.py

[## [FILE: src/financial_rag/utils/exceptions.py ]]

189
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:02,000
Now let's create our exception hierarchy.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/utils/exceptions.py

190
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:08,000
First, let's look at the base FinRAGError class.
It takes a message and an optional cause.

191
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:14,000
The cause is the original exception that triggered this one.
This preserves the full stack trace.

192
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:20,000
The string representation includes the cause if present.
This makes debugging much easier.

193
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:26,000
Now let's implement StorageError.
This is our base for all storage-layer errors.

194
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:32,000
DatabaseConnectionError is raised when we cannot connect to PostgreSQL.
This happens at startup if the database is unreachable.

195
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:38,000
DatabaseQueryError wraps SQLAlchemy or asyncpg exceptions
that occur during query execution.

196
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:44,000
CacheConnectionError and CacheOperationError do the same for Redis.
Connection for connectivity issues, Operation for read or write failures.

197
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:50,000
RecordNotFoundError is special.
It takes an entity name and an identifier.

198
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:56,000
For example, if we look up a filing by ID that doesn't exist,
we raise RecordNotFoundError with entity filing and the ID.

199
00:35:56,000 --> 00:36:02,000
This is analogous to HTTP 404 at the storage layer.
It tells you exactly what was missing.

200
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:08,000
Now IngestionError. This is our base for document ingestion errors.

201
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:14,000
SECFetchError is raised when the EDGAR API cannot be reached,
or returns an error like a rate limit violation.

202
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:20,000
DocumentParseError is raised when a document cannot be parsed.
This could be a corrupted PDF or invalid HTML.

203
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:26,000
DuplicateFilingError is raised when we try to ingest a filing
that already exists in the database.

204
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:32,000
It takes a ticker symbol and a file hash.
The error message tells you exactly which filing was duplicated.

205
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:38,000
ProcessingError is our base for document processing errors.
ChunkingError is raised when document chunking fails.

206
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:44,000
For example, if a document cannot be tokenised or split
within our configured constraints.

207
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:50,000
RetrievalError is our base for retrieval-layer errors.
EmbeddingError is raised when the embedding API returns an error or times out.

208
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:56,000
This includes OpenAI rate-limit errors.
VectorSearchError is raised when a pgvector similarity search fails.

209
00:36:56,000 --> 00:37:02,000
Finally, ConfigurationError.
This is raised when the application detects a fatal misconfiguration
that wasn't caught at settings validation time.

210
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:08,000
Now let me explain why this hierarchy matters.

211
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:14,000
First, it makes error handling precise.
You can catch exactly what you need and ignore what you don't.

212
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:20,000
For example, in a web endpoint, you might catch SECFetchError
and return a 503 Service Unavailable response.

213
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:26,000
But you would not want to catch ConfigurationError the same way.
That should crash the application immediately.

214
00:37:26,000 --> 00:37:32,000
Second, the cause parameter preserves the original error.
When we wrap an exception, we don't lose the stack trace.

215
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:38,000
Third, consistent exception types make logging and monitoring easier.
You can track how many DatabaseConnectionError events occur each day.

216
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:44,000
Our exception hierarchy is complete.
Every error in the application now has a clear home.

217
00:37:44,000 --> 00:37:50,000
Now let's update the utils package __init__.py to export all these exceptions.


[## [FILE: src/financial_rag/storage/repositories/base.py — Generic Async Repository Base]]

392
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:22,000
Before we create specific repositories for filings and chunks,
we need a base repository that all other repositories inherit from.

393
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:28,000
The repository pattern abstracts database operations.
It gives us a clean interface for working with our data models.

394
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:34,000
Instead of writing raw SQLAlchemy queries everywhere,
we encapsulate them inside repository classes.

395
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:40,000
Let me explain the key design decisions.

396
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:46,000
First, repositories borrow sessions. They do not own transactions.
The service layer decides when to commit or roll back.

397
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:52,000
This is important. If a repository committed after every operation,
you couldn't group multiple operations into one transaction.

398
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:58,000
Second, every database operation wraps exceptions in DatabaseQueryError.
This gives us consistent error handling across all repositories.

399
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:04,000
Third, methods like add and add_many flush but do not commit.
Flush sends the SQL to the database. Commit makes it permanent.

400
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:10,000
The caller controls the transaction boundary.
This is critical for idempotent ingestion.

401
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:16,000
Let's create the base repository.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/storage/repositories/base.py



[## [FILE: src/financial_rag/storage/repositories/base.py]]

402
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:22,000
First, imports. We need logging, Generic and TypeVar from typing, and UUID.
From SQLAlchemy, we import func and select.

403
00:56:22,000 --> 00:56:28,000
From sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio, we import AsyncSession.
From our utils, we import DatabaseQueryError and RecordNotFoundError.

404
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:34,000
Now define our type variable.
ModelT is a TypeVar that represents any SQLAlchemy ORM model.

405
00:56:34,000 --> 00:56:40,000
This makes BaseRepository a generic class.
When we subclass it, we specify the concrete model type.

406
00:56:40,000 --> 00:56:46,000
For example, FilingsRepository would be BaseRepository with Filing as the model.

407
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:52,000
The class declaration uses Generic with ModelT.
This tells Python that the class works with a type parameter.

408
00:56:52,000 --> 00:56:58,000
The docstring explains the key contract.
Subclasses must declare a model_class attribute.

409
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:04,000
And all methods receive an AsyncSession injected from the caller.
Repositories do NOT own sessions. They borrow them.

410
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:10,000
The __init__ method stores the session.
Every repository instance is tied to one database session.

411
00:57:10,000 --> 00:57:16,000
Now let's look at the create methods.

412
00:57:16,000 --> 00:57:22,000
The add method takes an ORM instance and adds it to the session.
It flushes to send the SQL to the database but does NOT commit.

413
00:57:22,000 --> 00:57:28,000
After flushing, we refresh the instance.
This loads any database-generated values like auto-incrementing IDs.

414
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:34,000
The add_many method does the same thing for a list of instances.
It uses add_all which is more efficient than calling add in a loop.

415
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:40,000
If the list is empty, we return early to avoid unnecessary work.

416
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:46,000
Now the read methods.

417
00:57:46,000 --> 00:57:52,000
get_by_id fetches a single record by its primary key.
It uses the session.get method which is optimized for primary key lookups.

418
00:57:52,000 --> 00:57:58,000
If the instance is None, meaning no record exists,
we raise RecordNotFoundError with the model name and ID.

419
00:57:58,000 --> 00:58:04,000
get_by_id_or_none does the same thing but returns None instead of raising.
This is useful for optional lookups.

420
00:58:04,000 --> 00:58:10,000
list_all returns all records with pagination.
We use limit and offset to control how many records are returned.

421
00:58:10,000 --> 00:58:16,000
The docstring has a warning.
Do not use this on large tables without filters.
Concrete repositories should add WHERE clauses.

422
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:22,000
The count method returns the total number of records.
It uses SQLAlchemy's func.count to generate a COUNT query.

423
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:28,000
Now the update method.
This takes an instance and keyword arguments for the fields to update.

424
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:34,000
We iterate through each field, check if the instance has the attribute,
and then set the new value.

425
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:40,000
After updating, we flush and refresh the instance.
Refresh reloads the instance from the database with the new values.

426
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:46,000
If a field name doesn't exist, we raise DatabaseQueryError
with a helpful message.

427
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:52,000
Finally, the delete methods.

428
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:58,000
The delete method performs a hard delete.
It removes the record from the database completely.

429
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:04,000
The soft_delete method performs a soft delete.
It sets is_active to False instead of deleting the record.

430
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:10,000
Soft delete is useful when you want to keep historical data.
The record still exists in the database but is filtered out of most queries.

431
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:16,000
Note that soft_delete requires the model to have an is_active column.
It calls the update method we just defined.

432
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:22,000
Let me summarize the key principles.

433
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:28,000
First, repositories borrow sessions. They do not own transactions.
The service layer decides when to commit or roll back.

434
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:34,000
Second, every database operation wraps exceptions in DatabaseQueryError.
This gives us a consistent error type across all repositories.

435
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:40,000
Third, methods like add and add_many flush but do not commit.
This allows the caller to group multiple operations into one transaction.

436
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:46,000
Our base repository is complete.
Concrete repositories will inherit from this and add domain-specific queries.



[## [FILE: src/financial_rag/storage/repositories/filings.py — Filings Repository with Deduplication]]

437
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:52,000
Now let's create our first concrete repository for the filings table.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/storage/repositories/filings.py

438
00:59:52,000 --> 00:59:58,000
This repository handles all database operations for SEC filings.
It inherits from our BaseRepository.

439
00:59:58,000 --> 01:00:04,000
First, let's understand the imports.
We need logging, date from datetime, and UUID.

440
01:00:04,000 --> 01:00:10,000
From SQLAlchemy, we import Boolean, Date, Integer, SmallInteger, String, and select.
From sqlalchemy.orm, we import Mapped and mapped_column.

441
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:16,000
From our application, we import Base from storage.database,
BaseRepository from repositories.base, and DatabaseQueryError from utils.

442
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:22,000
Now let's define our ORM model class called Filing.
This maps Python code to the filings table in PostgreSQL.

443
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:28,000
The __tablename__ is set to filings, matching our schema.
Each field corresponds to a column in the database.

444
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:34,000
