[## [SECTION: SEC EDGAR Ingestor — Understanding the Problem]]

224
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:32,000
Now let's build our SEC EDGAR ingestor.
This is the heart of Phase 2. It downloads SEC filings directly from the government's EDGAR system.

225
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:38,000
But before we write code, let me explain the challenges we need to solve.
Three big ones.

226
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:44,000
Challenge one. Rate limiting.
EDGAR enforces a hard limit of 10 requests per second per IP address.

227
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:50,000
If you exceed this, they return HTTP 429 and may block your IP.
A naive implementation that fires all requests at once would get throttled immediately.

228
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:56,000
We need a rate limiter that spaces requests evenly.
Exactly one request every 100 milliseconds.

229
00:38:56,000 --> 00:39:02,000
Challenge two. Deduplication.
The same filing might be downloaded multiple times.
If your ingestion job runs daily, you'll re-download the same 10-K over and over.

230
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:08,000
We need a way to detect if a filing has already been ingested.
SHA-256 hashing of the content gives us a unique fingerprint.

231
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:14,000
Even if the filing is re-filed with a different date, the content hash changes.
We can detect duplicates reliably.

232
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:20,000
Challenge three. Transient errors.
The EDGAR API occasionally returns 5xx errors or times out.

233
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:26,000
We need automatic retries with exponential backoff.
If a request fails, wait 2 seconds, try again. Wait 4 seconds, try again. Wait 8 seconds, then give up.

234
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:32,000
Let me show you how we solve all three challenges.
We'll build a token bucket rate limiter using asyncio Semaphore.

235
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:38,000
We'll use tenacity for retries with exponential backoff.
And we'll compute SHA-256 hashes for deduplication.

236
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:44,000
We'll also cache raw HTML to disk.
So if your ingestion job fails halfway, you don't re-download everything.

237
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:50,000
Let's create the file.
src/financial_rag/ingestion/sec_ingestor.py


[## [FILE: src/financial_rag/ingestion/sec_ingestor.py — Async SEC EDGAR Client with Rate Limiting, Retries, and Deduplication]]


238
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:56,000
First, imports. We need asyncio, hashlib, logging, and datetime.
From typing, we import TYPE_CHECKING for conditional imports.

239
00:39:56,000 --> 00:40:02,000
We use httpx for async HTTP requests.
And tenacity for retries with exponential backoff.

240
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:08,000
From our application, we import get_settings
and SECFetchError from exceptions.

241
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:14,000
Now define the EDGAR base URLs and supported filing types.
We only support 10-K, 10-Q, 8-K, 20-F, DEF 14A, and S-1.

242
00:40:14,000 --> 00:40:20,000
Component one. The rate limiter.
EDGAR enforces 10 requests per second per IP address.

243
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:26,000
Our token bucket rate limiter uses an asyncio semaphore.
It allows at most RPS concurrent requests.

244
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:32,000
Then it sleeps for the interval between releases.
For 10 requests per second, that's 100 milliseconds.

245
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:38,000
When you enter the rate limiter using async with, it acquires the semaphore.
When you exit, it sleeps and then releases.

246
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:44,000
The result is exactly 10 requests per second, evenly spaced.
Never burst, never throttled.

247
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:50,000
Now the FilingMetadata class.
This is a lightweight value object returned by list_filings.

248
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:56,000
It uses __slots__ for memory efficiency.
Each instance stores ticker, filing type, fiscal year and quarter,
filed date, accession number, and source URL.

249
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:02,000
The __repr__ method gives us a readable string for debugging.
We pass this metadata to download_filing to fetch the actual content.

250
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:08,000
Now the SECIngestor class itself.
This is the main entry point for all EDGAR operations.

251
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:14,000
In __init__, we load settings, create the rate limiter,
and initialize the HTTP client as None.

252
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:20,000
We use async context managers for proper cleanup.
__aenter__ creates the httpx client with our User-Agent header.

253
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:26,000
EDGAR requires a descriptive User-Agent identifying your application.
Without this, your requests may be blocked.

254
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:32,000
__aexit__ closes the client and releases resources.
Now the public API methods.

255
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:38,000
Method one. list_filings.
This returns metadata for the most recent N years of filings.

256
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:44,000
First, we validate the filing type is supported.
If not, we raise SECFetchError with helpful message.

257
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:50,000
We resolve the ticker to a CIK number.
CIK stands for Central Index Key, EDGAR's unique identifier for companies.

258
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:56,000
Then we fetch the submissions JSON and parse it.
The result is a list of FilingMetadata objects, newest first.

259
00:41:56,000 --> 00:42:02,000
Method two. download_filing.
This downloads the primary document for a filing.

260
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:08,000
First, we check if a cached version exists in raw_dir.
If yes, we return the cached content and its hash.

261
00:42:08,000 --> 00:42:14,000
If not, we fetch the document from the source URL.
We compute the SHA-256 hash of the content.

262
00:42:14,000 --> 00:42:20,000
A SHA-256 hash is a 64-character fingerprint.
If the content changes by even one character, the hash changes completely.

263
00:42:20,000 --> 00:42:26,000
We then cache the content if raw_dir was provided.
And return the content and hash as a tuple.

264
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:32,000
Method three. check_duplicate.
This is a utility that checks if a filing already exists in our database.

265
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:38,000
We get the database client, create a session,
and use the FilingsRepository to check by hash.

266
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:44,000
Now the internal EDGAR API calls.
Each one is decorated with tenacity's retry.

267
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:50,000
Let me explain the retry decorator carefully.
retry_if_exception_type means only retry on SECFetchError.

268
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:56,000
stop_after_attempt of 3 means maximum 3 total attempts.
wait_exponential means wait 2 seconds, then 4, then 8.

269
00:42:56,000 --> 00:43:02,000
reraise True means after exhaustion, re-raise the original error.
Any other exception type bypasses the retry entirely.

270
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:08,000
_resolve_cik fetches the company_tickers.json file from EDGAR.
This maps ticker symbols to CIK numbers.

271
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:14,000
We iterate through the entries looking for a matching ticker.
If found, we return the CIK padded to 10 digits.

272
00:43:14,000 --> 00:43:20,000
If not found, we raise SECFetchError.
_fetch_submissions fetches the full submissions JSON for a CIK.

273
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:26,000
_fetch_document downloads the raw content of a filing.
We set the Host header to www.sec.gov explicitly.

274
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:32,000
Notice that every HTTP call is wrapped with the rate limiter.
async with self._rate_limiter ensures we never exceed 10 requests per second.

275
00:43:32,000 --> 00:43:38,000
Now _parse_submissions.
This extracts the relevant filings from the JSON response.

276
00:43:38,000 --> 00:43:44,000
We look at the recent filings array.
We filter to the requested filing type and collect up to years many results.

277
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:50,000
We skip duplicates by tracking seen fiscal years.
We construct the source URL by combining the CIK, accession number, and primary document.

278
00:43:50,000 --> 00:43:56,000
Finally, cache helpers for raw filing storage.
_cache_path builds a path like ticker slash filing type slash FYyear.html.

279
00:43:56,000 --> 00:44:02,000
_check_cache reads from disk if the file exists.
_write_cache writes the content to disk, creating parent directories as needed.

280
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:08,000
Let me summarize the flow for ingesting a filing.

281
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:14,000
First, call list_filings to get metadata.
This resolves the ticker to a CIK and parses the submissions.

282
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:20,000
Second, call download_filing with the metadata.
This fetches the raw HTML and returns the content plus SHA-256 hash.

283
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:26,000
Third, check if the hash already exists in the database.
If it does, skip to avoid duplicates.

284
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:32,000
If not, proceed to parsing, chunking, embedding, and storage.
All with automatic retries and rate limiting.

285
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:38,000
Our SEC ingestor is complete.
It respects EDGAR's limits, handles failures gracefully, and prevents duplicates.

[## [SECTION: HTML Parser — Cleaning Messy SEC Filings]]

286
00:44:38,000 --> 00:44:44,000
Now that we can download SEC filings, we need to parse them.
SEC filings are messy documents. Very messy.

287
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:50,000
They contain SGML headers before the HTML starts.
XBRL inline tags for machine-readable data.

288
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:56,000
Exhibit sections that are just boilerplate.
And inconsistent heading formats for sections.

289
00:44:56,000 --> 00:45:02,000
Our job is to strip all of that away.
We want clean, section-tagged text ready for chunking.

290
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:08,000
Let me explain the strategy.

291
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:14,000
Step one. Strip the SGML header.
SEC filings begin with SGML metadata before the first HTML tag.
We search for the first HTML tag and discard everything before it.

292
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:20,000
Step two. Remove noise tags.
Script tags, style tags, meta tags, SVG tags.
XBRL inline tags like ix:nonfraction and ix:nonumeric.

293
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:26,000
These contain no human-readable text.
We remove them entirely from the document tree.

294
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:32,000
Step three. Extract clean text.
We use BeautifulSoup's get_text with newline separators.

295
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:38,000
Then we normalize whitespace. Collapse runs of spaces into single spaces.
Collapse excessive blank lines to at most two in a row.

296
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:44,000
Step four. Remove boilerplate patterns.
Page numbers like dash space 42 space dash. Table of contents markers.

297
00:45:44,000 --> 00:45:50,000
EDGAR header fields. Long separator lines of equals signs or dashes.
These add no value to the content.

298
00:45:50,000 --> 00:45:56,000
Step five. Detect sections.
We split the text into lines and look for heading patterns.

299
00:45:56,000 --> 00:46:02,000
Regular expressions match phrases like "management discussion and analysis".
Or "risk factors". Or "financial statements".

300
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:08,000
When we find a heading, we group all lines until the next heading.
That becomes a section.

301
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:14,000
Sections shorter than 200 characters are discarded as false positives.
If no sections are found, we return the full text as a "General" section.

302
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:20,000
Let's implement this.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/ingestion/parsers/html_parser.py


[## [FILE: src/financial_rag/ingestion/parsers/html_parser.py — HTML Parser for SEC Filings with Section Detection]]


303
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:26,000
First, imports. We need logging, re for regular expressions, and dataclasses.
From bs4, we import BeautifulSoup and Tag.

304
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:32,000
From our application, we import DocumentParseError from exceptions.

305
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:38,000
Now define our section detection patterns.
This is a list of regular expression patterns mapped to canonical section names.

306
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:44,000
For example, patterns matching "management discussion and analysis"
map to the canonical name "MD&A".

307
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:50,000
Order matters. First match wins.
We have patterns for Risk Factors, Market Risk, Business, Financial Statements,
Balance Sheet, Income Statement, Cash Flow, and more.

308
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:56,000
Next, define tags that never contain useful text.
Script, style, meta, link, head, noscript, SVG, and image tags.

309
00:46:56,000 --> 00:47:02,000
We also discard XBRL inline tags like ix:nonfraction and ix:nonumeric.
These are machine-readable tags, not human text.

310
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:08,000
Now the ParsedSection dataclass.
This represents a single identified section from a filing.

311
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:14,000
It has a name, the section text, and a computed character count.
The __repr__ method gives us readable output for debugging.

312
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:20,000
Next, the ParsedFiling dataclass.
This is the complete result of parsing a filing.

313
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:26,000
It contains ticker, filing type, fiscal year,
the full cleaned text, and a list of sections.

314
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:32,000
The get_section method lets you retrieve a specific section by name.
If not found, it returns None.

315
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:38,000
Now the main HTMLParser class.
This is where the parsing logic lives.

316
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:44,000
The parse method is the public entry point.
It takes raw HTML, ticker, filing type, and optional fiscal year.

317
00:47:44,000 --> 00:47:50,000
It returns a ParsedFiling object with all extracted content.

318
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:56,000
Inside parse, we perform five steps.
Let me walk through each one.

319
00:47:56,000 --> 00:48:02,000
Step one. strip the SGML header.
SEC filings begin with SGML metadata before the HTML starts.

320
00:48:02,000 --> 00:48:08,000
We search for the first HTML tag.
Everything before that is discarded.

321
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:14,000
Step two. parse with BeautifulSoup using the lxml parser.
Step three. remove noise tags entirely.

322
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:20,000
The _remove_noise_tags method finds every tag in our discard list
and calls decompose to remove them from the tree.

323
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:26,000
Then it removes any tag that has no visible text content.
Empty tags just add noise.

324
00:48:26,000 --> 00:48:32,000
Step four. extract clean text.
We use soup.get_text with a newline separator to preserve line structure.

325
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:38,000
Then we normalize whitespace.
Collapse runs of spaces, but preserve newlines.

326
00:48:38,000 --> 00:48:44,000
We collapse excessive blank lines to at most two in a row.
This keeps the text readable without giant gaps.

327
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:50,000
Then we run boilerplate removal.
We strip out page numbers, table of contents markers, and EDGAR header fields.

328
00:48:50,000 --> 00:48:56,000
We also remove long separator lines of equals signs or dashes.
These add no value to the content.

329
00:48:56,000 --> 00:49:02,000
Step five. detect sections.
This is where we identify the major sections within the filing.

330
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:08,000
We split the text into lines.
Then we look for lines that match our section heading patterns.

331
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:14,000
Section headings are typically short — less than 200 characters.
If a line is too long, it's probably not a heading.

332
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:20,000
When we find a heading, we record its line index and section name.
We build a list of heading positions.

333
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:26,000
If no sections are detected at all,
we return the full text under a "General" section.

334
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:32,000
If we have headings, we iterate through them.
For each heading, we take all lines from its position to the next heading.

335
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:38,000
We skip duplicate section names.
We also skip sections shorter than 200 characters as false positives.

336
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:44,000
The result is a list of ParsedSection objects.
Each contains a section name and its cleaned text.

337
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:50,000
Let me summarize what the parser does from start to finish.

338
00:49:50,000 --> 00:49:56,000
Input. raw SEC filing HTML with SGML headers and XBRL tags.
Output. a ParsedFiling with full clean text and per-section breakdown.

339
00:49:56,000 --> 00:50:02,000
We strip the SGML header, parse with BeautifulSoup,
remove noise tags, extract and clean the text.

340
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:08,000
Then we detect sections using regex patterns.
Sections shorter than 200 characters are discarded as false positives.

341
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:14,000
The result is structured text ready for chunking and embedding.
Our HTML parser is complete.


[## [SECTION: Text Parser — Cleaning and Normalizing Financial Text]]


342
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:20,000
Now we have clean HTML text, but it still needs more processing.
The text parser runs after the HTML parser and before chunking.

343
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:26,000
What problems does it solve?
First, Unicode normalization.

344
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:32,000
SEC filings contain all sorts of special characters.
Ligatures like the fi character that looks like one symbol but is actually two letters.

345
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:38,000
Accented characters, non-breaking spaces, em dashes.
We normalize everything to a standard form called NFKC.

346
00:50:38,000 --> 00:50:44,000
Second, removing noise.
URLs, email addresses, control characters that aren't visible.
Four or more consecutive newlines.

347
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:50,000
Third, normalizing financial number formatting.
Dollar signs and commas fragment tokenization.

348
00:50:50,000 --> 00:50:56,000
For example, the string "1,234" becomes two tokens. "1" and "234".
After normalization, "1234" is a single token.

349
00:50:56,000 --> 00:51:02,000
Fourth, extracting financial metrics.
We use regex patterns to find revenue figures, net income, earnings per share.

350
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:08,000
"Revenue of X billion" becomes a key-value pair.
revenue equals the numeric value scaled to full dollars.

351
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:14,000
These metrics get stored in the JSONB column of financial_chunks.
This allows fast filtering and aggregation without re-parsing the text.

352
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:20,000
Let me show you the implementation.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/ingestion/parsers/text_parser.py


[## [FILE: src/financial_rag/ingestion/parsers/text_parser.py — Text Cleaner and Financial Metric Extractor]]

353
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:26,000
First, imports. We need logging, re for regular expressions,
and unicodedata for Unicode normalisation.

354
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:32,000
From our application, we import DocumentParseError from exceptions.

355
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:38,000
Now define noise patterns.
These are regular expressions that match content we want to remove.

356
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:44,000
We remove URLs starting with http or https.
We remove email addresses, control characters, and four or more consecutive newlines.

357
00:51:44,000 --> 00:51:50,000
Next, number normalisation patterns.
These preserve the semantic meaning while cleaning formatting.

358
00:51:50,000 --> 00:51:58,000
We remove dollar signs before numbers.
So dollar sign 1 comma 234 becomes just 1234.

359
00:51:58,000 --> 00:52:04,000
We remove commas in numbers.
So 1 comma 234 comma 567 becomes 1234567.

360
00:52:04,000 --> 00:52:10,000
And we normalise percentages.
12.5 space percent becomes 12.5 percent with no space.

361
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:16,000
Now the TextParser class.
It has three public methods. clean, normalise_numbers, and extract_metrics.

362
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:22,000
Let's start with the clean method.
This is the full cleaning pipeline.

363
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:28,000
Step one. Unicode normalisation using NFKC.
NFKC converts ligatures and normalises accented characters.

364
00:52:28,000 --> 00:52:34,000
For example, the ligature character for "fi" becomes two separate letters.
And an accented e becomes a plain e.

365
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:40,000
Step two. remove noise patterns.
We loop through each pattern and replace matches with a space.

366
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:46,000
Step three. normalise whitespace within lines.
We collapse runs of spaces and tabs into a single space.

367
00:52:46,000 --> 00:52:52,000
Step four. collapse excessive blank lines.
We allow at most two consecutive blank lines.

368
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:58,000
Then we join the lines back together and strip the result.
This gives us clean, readable text.

369
00:52:58,000 --> 00:53:04,000
Now the normalise_numbers method.
This applies our number normalisation patterns to the text.

370
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:10,000
It removes dollar signs and commas from numbers.
And fixes spacing around percentage signs.

371
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:16,000
This is important for chunking.
If we leave dollar signs and commas, they fragment tokenisation.

372
00:53:16,000 --> 00:53:22,000
For example, "1,234" becomes two tokens. "1" and "234".
After normalisation, "1234" is a single token.

373
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:28,000
Now the extract_metrics method.
This extracts numerical financial metrics using regex patterns.

374
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:34,000
It returns a dictionary of metric names to numeric values.
This will be stored in the metrics JSONB column of the financial_chunks table.

375
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:40,000
First, we define a helper called _safe_float.
It removes commas from a string and attempts to convert to float.

376
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:46,000
If conversion fails, it returns None.
This prevents exceptions from malformed numbers.

377
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:52,000
Now revenue extraction.
We look for patterns like revenue of X billion or total revenue of X million.

378
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:58,000
When we find a match, we extract the number and the scale.
Then we pass both to _apply_scale to get the full value.

379
00:53:58,000 --> 00:54:04,000
Next, net income extraction.
Similar pattern but looking for net income, net earnings, or net loss.

380
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:10,000
EPS extraction for earnings per share.
We look for EPS or earnings per diluted share followed by a dollar figure.

381
00:54:10,000 --> 00:54:16,000
And margin extraction for operating, gross, or net margin.
We look for a number followed by a percent sign.

382
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:22,000
Finally, the _apply_scale helper.
It converts a scaled value to its full numeric form.

383
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:28,000
If the scale is billion, multiply by 1 billion.
If million, multiply by 1 million. If thousand, multiply by 1 thousand.

384
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:34,000
If no scale is provided, return the value unchanged.

385
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:40,000
Let me summarize the text parser's role in the pipeline.

386
00:54:40,000 --> 00:54:46,000
The HTML parser gives us raw cleaned text.
But that text still has URLs, emails, and messy number formatting.

387
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:52,000
The text parser cleans all of that.
It normalises Unicode, strips noise, and standardises number formats.

388
00:54:52,000 --> 00:54:58,000
It also extracts key financial metrics.
Revenue, net income, EPS, and margins go into a dictionary.

389
00:54:58,000 --> 00:55:04,000
This dictionary will be stored in the metrics JSONB column.
That column is indexed with GIN for efficient querying.

390
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:10,000
The cleaned text then goes to the chunking processor.
The metrics go to the database alongside the embeddings.

391
00:55:10,000 --> 00:55:16,000
Our text parser is complete.
Text is now clean, normalised, and enriched with metrics.

